  1. (5pts) Professor M. J. Canino looks at your graph in Part A and says to you, The passengers were equally likely to belong to any of the three classes. You obviously disagree. You tell Professor Canino to just look at the graph, but they are still unconvinced, arguing that what you see in the graph could just be due to random noise and may not be an actual significant difference.

From the graphs alone, are you able to definitively state whether or not there is a statistically significant difference amongst the proportions of classes? State yes or no, and then provide a one-sentence explanation for your answer.

No: From the graphs alone, you are not able to definitively state whether or not there is a statistically significant difference amongst the proportions of classes; we need to conduct a formal statistical test to do this.

  1. (6 points) To provide more explicit evidence of statistical significance, what kind of statistical test could you use to show that the passengers are not equally likely to belong to any of the three classes?

After stating the test, run the statistical test, and then formally interpret the results from the test in 1-3 sentences. To receive full credit for this question, you must (1) display the code you used to run the test, (2) state the p-value from the test, and (3) state your formal conclusion from the test. (Hint: Even if you do not know the syntax/code for running this test in R, you can easily figure it out using Google. Just Google something like, How to perform ___ test in R.)

We can use a chi-square test for equal proportions. Here is the code to run the test:

chisq.test(table(titanic$Pclass))
## 
##  Chi-squared test for given probabilities
## 
## data:  table(titanic$Pclass)
## X-squared = 87.761, df = 2, p-value < 2.2e-16

We see that the p-value is quite small - less than \(2.2 \cdot 10^{-16}\). Thus, we reject the null hypothesis that the proportions among the different classes are equal, thereby concluding that they are not all equal (i.e., at least one pair of proportions are not equal). Note that this is different from concluding that all the proportions are not equal to each other.

  1. (3pts) Write an R function called abssum that takes four inputs: a, b, x, and y, and returns the quantity \(ax + b|y|\). Test your function and demonstrate that it works for at least three different combinations of the inputs.

Heres the function abssum():

abssum <- function(a,b,x,y){
  return(a*x + b*abs(y))
}

all(

We see that it calculates abssum2(1,1), abssum2(2,2), , abssum2(10,10) That is, abssum2(i,i) for i in 1:10, applying the calculation across the vectors. This happens because all of the calculations within abssum2() are vectorized.

  1. (3pts) Use help(rnorm) to learn about the function rnorm, which generates Normal random variables. Generate 5000 independent standard Normal random variables (i.e., a Normal distribution with mean 0 and variance 1) and assign them to a variable called Z. Repeat the same procedure and assign the new values to W. Then, uncomment the following code (which uses the base R plot() function to produce a scatterplot):
Z = rnorm(5000)
W = rnorm(5000)
plot(W, abssum2(x = Z, y = W), cex = .5, pch = 16, xlab = "W", ylab = "Z + |W|")

Describe the graph that shows up, and explain why this happens.

Since abssum2(x = Z, y = W) applies the function \(1\cdot z + 1\cdot |w|\) to each pair \((z,w)\) in our 2 vectors, we obtain a V-shape of scattered dots (which looks a lot like a heart). The V-shape is due to the absolute value part of abssum2(). If the plot were |W| vs W, it would have a perfect V shape. The random scatter occurs due to the normal variation of Z.

  1. (10pts) Now were going to work towards adding confidence intervals to the plot you made in Part B. For this part, write a function called getPropCI() that computes the 95% confidence intervals for the proportion of each manufacturer. Your function should take in a frequency table freqTable produced by the table() function:
freqTable = table(UScereal$mfr)

To get you started, below is some template code. As you can see from the template code, you must use freqTable to do three things:

  • Compute the total sample size in UScereal
  • Compute the proportions of each category of mfr
  • Compute the standard error of the proportions

Thus, you only need to write three additional lines of code for getPropCI().

getPropCI = function(freqTable, alpha = 0.05){
  #the total sample size is
  n = sum(freqTable)
  #the proportions are
  proportions = freqTable/n
  #the standard error for proportions is
  SE = sqrt((proportions*(1-proportions))/n)
  #the confidence intervals are
  CI.lower = proportions - qnorm(1-alpha/2)*SE
  CI.upper = proportions + qnorm(1-alpha/2)*SE
  CIs = rbind(CI.lower, CI.upper)
  return(CIs)
}

After youve written getPropCI(), uncomment the following line of code such that the confidence intervals display:

getPropCI(freqTable)

## CI.lower 0.2234282 0.2093891 -0.004853711 0.0544975 0.01214341 0.01214341
## CI.upper 0.4534949 0.4367648  0.097161404 0.2224256 0.14170274 0.14170274

After youve successfully displayed your confidence intervals above, answer the following: Is there anything non-intuitive with any of the confidence intervals youve computed? State Yes or No, and give a 1-2 sentence explanation.

Yes, the confidence interval for the proportion of Nabisco manufacturers contains negative numbers, which is non-intuitive, because proportions are strictly between 0 and 1.

  1. (6 points) Now were going to interpret the confidence intervals you visualized in Part E. Lets say that Professor M. Zauner is particularly interested in cereal, and asks the following questions:

  1. (8pts) In Part F, Professor Zauner asked you to make several pairwise comparisons between one manufacturer and another. You can find that there are 15 different pairwise comparisons you could make from your bar graph. As a result, if we attempt to make multiple pairwise comparisons from a single graph with 95% confidence intervals, our chance of making a Type 1 error is greater than 5%.

To address this issue, make a bar graph similar to Part E, but with confidence intervals that incorporate the Bonferroni correction for 15 comparisons. (We will discuss the Bonferroni correction in class, but you can also see the hint below if youre not familiar with this correction.) In other words, your graph here should be exactly the same as the graph in Part E, but with wider confidence intervals that incorporate the Bonferroni correction. Then, outside of your code, discuss (in 1-2 sentences) how you constructed the Bonferroni confidence intervals. After youve done that, answer Professor Zauners same questions from Part F, but using the graph youve made here.

Hint: In general, \(\alpha\)-level confidence intervals are constructed using the Normal quantile \(z_{1-\alpha/2}\). When we construct 95% confidence intervals, \(\alpha = 0.05\), and thus we use \(z_{1 - \alpha/2} = z_{0.975}\) (computed with qnorm(0.975)). This is exactly what we did with propCI() in Part C, where we set alpha = 0.05 by default. When we use the Bonferroni correction, \(\alpha\) is instead set to \(0.05/k\), where \(k\) is equal to the number of comparisons. Thus, for this part, all you need to do is appropriately use propCI(), which youve already written, and then make a new graph.

First, we will create confidence intervals that incorporate the Bonferroni correction:

countCIs.bonf = nrow(UScereal)*getPropCI(freqTable, alpha = 0.05/15)

UScereal.CIs.bonf = data.frame(
  mfr = names(table(UScereal$mfr)), #this should be the name of each manufacturer
  counts = as.numeric(table(UScereal$mfr)), #this should be the counts of each manufacturer
  lower = countCIs.bonf[1,], #this should be the lower-bound of the 95% CI
  upper = countCIs.bonf[2,]) #this should be the upper-bound of the 95% CI

Note that our process for creating these confidence intervals is exactly the same as what we did in Part D; the only difference is that we set alpha = 0.05/15 instead of the default alpha = 0.05.

Now, here is the desired plot:

ggplot(data = UScereal.CIs.bonf, aes(mfr, counts)) + geom_col(fill = "darkgreen") +
 geom_errorbar(aes(ymin=lower, ymax=upper)) + labs(x = "Manufacturer", y = "Count", title = "Frequency of US Cereal Manufacturers \n (along with 95% Confidence Intervals with Bonferroni Correction)") +
theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5))

Note that all we did was copy-and-paste our code from Part E, but used UScereal.CIs.bonf instead of UScereal.CIs within ggplot(). (We also changed the title slightly.)
